# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} A situation that is badly [[planned]], or [[illogical]].
#: ''Mayor Smith's new traffic rules were a '''bad joke'''.''
#* {{quote-text|year=1938|author=Robert William Seton-Watson|title=Britain and the Dictators: A Survey of Post-war British Policy|page=172|passage=Disarmament must be total, or it was merely "a '''bad joke'''".}}
#* {{quote-text|year=1940|author=Kenelm Foss|title=Here Lies Richard Brinsley Sheridan|page=267|passage=But it is amusing to note that whenever the tables were turned on him he would mutter "'''Bad joke'''. Very '''bad joke'''".}}
#* {{quote-text|year=1986|author=Claire Martin|title=The Legacy|page=25|passage="Maybe it was just a '''bad joke'''. " "A '''bad joke'''!" shrieked David, and in that cry I could detect all the ancient terrors of Israel.}}
#* '''2002''', Mikael af Malmborg, Bo Stråth, ''The Meaning of Europe'', page 272
#*: It is this '''bad joke''' which, almost one century later, was still to be found in the government's campaign of 'We are Europe' from 1994.
#* {{quote-text|year=2002|author=Cesar Guerra|title=Hijacked to Havana!|page=28|passage=This might be a '''bad joke''' for you and to the people able to fly back to Miami but this is not a joke at all to me.}}
#* '''2007''', Keith Olbarmann, ''Countdown with Keith Olbermann''
#*: Upon seeing Keyes' face, 15 {{w|MSNBC}} executives promptly resigned. {{w|Alan Keyes}}? ''{{w|Alan Keyes is Making Sense}}'' Alan Keyes? You've gotta be kidding me. Incidentally, the name of that show always seemed like a '''bad joke''' to me.

